The patient has symptoms of abrupt onset of vaginal bleeding and severe lower back pain along with fetal heart monitoring showing delayed decelerations. These are all signs of placental abruption, which is the premature separation of a normally implanted placenta. The other options do not fit the symptoms presented by the patient.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient is experiencing vaginal bleeding, severe lower back pain, and contractions, which all point to a possible placental abruption. Delayed decelerations on fetal heart monitoring also suggest fetal distress. Premature separation of a normally implanted placenta is the most likely cause of these symptoms. Amniotic sac rupture prior to the start of uterine contractions or chorionic villi attaching to the decidua basalis or myometrium are less likely causes of these symptoms.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The symptoms of vaginal bleeding, lower back pain, large blood clots, and delayed decelerations on fetal monitoring suggest placental abruption. Premature separation of a normally implanted placenta is the most likely cause. Amniotic sac rupture prior to the start of uterine contractions (premature rupture of membranes) would present with continuous leaking of fluid, while chorionic villi attaching to the decidua basalis or myometrium would present with placenta previa or invasive placentation, respectively.
